The temperature of a gas is directly proportional to the average kinetic energy of its particles. The average kinetic energy of a particle in a gas is given by the equation:

{eq}KE = \frac{1}{2}mv^2

{/eq}

where {eq}m

{/eq} is the mass of the particle and {eq}v

{/eq} is the speed of the particle.

For Sample A:
{eq}KE_A = \frac{1}{2} \times 40 \times (950)^2

{/eq}

For Sample B:
{eq}KE_B = \frac{1}{2} \times 32 \times (750)^2

{/eq}

Calculating these values, we get:

{eq}KE_A \approx 1.18 \times 10^6 \text{ J}

{/eq}

{eq}KE_B \approx 5.625 \times 10^5 \text{ J}

{/eq}

Since {eq}KE_A

{/eq} is greater than {eq}KE_B

{/eq}, the average kinetic energy of the particles in Sample A is higher than that in Sample B. Therefore, Sample A has a higher temperature.

